<DOC><DOCNO> AP891101-0180 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-01-89 1856EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-01 0286</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0294</SECOND><HEAD>Snow, Rain Pester Motorists, Temperatures Rise in South</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Snow pestered motorists in portions of Colorado, North Dakotaand Wyoming, and rain drenched the nation's northeast, buttemperatures rose into the 70s in Texas and much of the lowerMississippi Valley on Wednesday.   Up to 5 inches of snow greeted morning commuters in the Denverarea, with as much as 6 inches in Fort Collins, Colo., and 8 inchesin the northern mountains.   Traffic was bumper to bumper along icy Colorado roads, withnumerous minor traffic accidents reported and a multi-car pileupsouth of Denver. No serious injuries were reported.   ``This is the storm that separates those prepared from those notprepared,'' said Denver public works spokeswoman Amy Lingg.   Denver skies cleared by afternoon. Snow also fell insoutheastern Colorado and parts of Minnesota, North Dakota andWyoming.   Elsewhere, showers produced about 1.5 inches of rain in Islip,N.Y., in a six-hour period ending at 7 a.m. EST. Providence, R.I.,got slightly less, with showers also plaguing parts of Maine andMassachusetts.   Temperatures dipped into the teens in the northern Rockies andthe northern High Plains regions, with single-digit readings inWyoming and Montana.   Butte and Cutbank in Montana tied as the morning cold spots inthe Lower 48 states, with lows of 2 degrees.   The leading edge of a cold arctic air mass pushed across easternOklahoma and central Texas.   Strong northerly winds prevailed across the central and southernhigh Plains. Temperatures were in the 20s and 30s in the northernPlains and in the 60s and 70s in southern and eastern Texas andacross much of the lower Mississippi Valley. Highs rose to the 80sacross Florida.</TEXT></DOC>